      "display_title": "Overview & Setup",
      "timestamp": "00:01",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening remarks on Daf 20 and the structure of Meilah",
          "display_title": "Daf 20 Setup",
          "timestamp": "00:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Review of previous concepts: forms of Meilah, Pegam, and Kedushah",
          "display_title": "Previous Concepts",
          "timestamp": "00:17"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Appropriation as a Form of Meilah: The Beam Case and Related Scenarios",
      "display_title": "Appropriation & Taking",
      "timestamp": "01:04",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Mishnah on stealing a beam: why taking possession is not yet Meilah until given to another",
          "display_title": "Beam Case",
          "timestamp": "01:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "Building a beam into one's house: Meilah requires actual benefit, not mere construction",
          "display_title": "Building in House",
          "timestamp": "04:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Giving money to a bathhouse attendant: completing the transaction as Meilah",
          "display_title": "Bathhouse Case",
          "timestamp": "05:14"
        },
        {
          "title": "Combined benefit from multiple recipients and the conceptual unity of Meilah across recipients",
          "display_title": "Combined Benefit",
          "timestamp": "09:14"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Gemara's Discussion of the Treasurer Exception and Definition of Taking",
      "display_title": "Treasurer Exception",
      "timestamp": "11:51",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Shmuel's answer: the temple treasurer has the right to handle materials, so taking is only Meilah when given out",
          "display_title": "Shmuel's Answer",
          "timestamp": "11:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "The question of why building into a house is not considered stealing outright",
          "display_title": "Building Question",
          "timestamp": "13:40"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Status of Built-in Items: Attached to Ground versus Chattel and Visible Benefit",
      "display_title": "Mechubar Lekarka",
      "timestamp": "14:03",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav's position: once you change the item (build it in), you have committed Meilah",
          "display_title": "Rav's Position",
          "timestamp": "14:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "The roof case: placing but not building into the house as mere benefit without taking",
          "display_title": "Roof Case",
          "timestamp": "14:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Digression on whether items attached to ground lose Meilah status: Rav Acha's answer on visible benefit",
          "display_title": "Visible Benefit",
          "timestamp": "17:44"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: items sanctified while still chattel retain Meilah status even after being built in",
          "display_title": "Sanctified Chattel",
          "timestamp": "22:09"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Shlichut (Agency) in Meilah: The Servant's Role and Violating the Bounds of Commission",
      "display_title": "Shlichut & Agency",
      "timestamp": "26:52",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction to Shlichut in Meilah: the agent's act is attributed to the sender unless the agent violates his orders",
          "display_title": "Shlichut Intro",
          "timestamp": "26:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "The liver versus meat case: when the agent gives something different from what was ordered",
          "display_title": "Liver vs Meat",
          "timestamp": "28:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "The escalating portions case: one piece ordered, two pieces given by agent, three taken by guests",
          "display_title": "Portions Case",
          "timestamp": "30:22"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Distinguishing Shlichut Bounds from Categorical Inclusion: The Liver-Meat Debate",
      "display_title": "Shlichut vs Category",
      "timestamp": "31:50",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Chisda's position: liver versus meat involves items requiring inquiry, violating agency bounds",
          "display_title": "Rav Chisda",
          "timestamp": "31:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye's refinement: even Rabbi Akiva agrees that ambiguous items require inquiry of the agent",
          "display_title": "Abaye's Refinement",
          "timestamp": "34:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's approval: the distinction between shlichut bounds and categorical classification is sound",
          "display_title": "Rava Approves",
          "timestamp": "35:55"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Meat-Bird-Fish Debate: What Counts as Meat in Vow and Intent",
      "display_title": "Meat Classification",
      "timestamp": "36:51",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "First opinion (implicit Rabbi Akiva): all organs and birds fall within the category of meat",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Akiva",
          "timestamp": "36:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabban Shimon ben Gamliel's position: organs and birds are not meat because they require inquiry",
          "display_title": "R. Shimon b. Gamliel",
          "timestamp": "38:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's challenge: why exclude fish but include birds if both require inquiry?",
          "display_title": "Fish Challenge",
          "timestamp": "40:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Papa's resolution: specific contexts (bloodletting, eye pain) determine what 'meat' means",
          "display_title": "Rav Papa",
          "timestamp": "42:18"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Two-Piece and Three-Piece Cases: Partial Violation of Shlichut",
      "display_title": "Partial Violation",
      "timestamp": "45:03",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Question of whether giving more than ordered completely negates the agency or remains valid for what was ordered",
          "display_title": "Agency Validity",
          "timestamp": "45:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Sheshet's answer: if the agent explicitly allocates one piece to the sender and one to himself, the agency remains intact",
          "display_title": "Rav Sheshet",
          "timestamp": "46:32"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion: the agent does not lose his agency even when going beyond the order, as long as he clearly delineates",
          "display_title": "Agency Preserved",
          "timestamp": "47:23"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
